Here's a recommended structure:

**1. Make HTTP calls injectable**

```csharp
// Register a named/typed HttpClient via IHttpClientFactory
services.AddHttpClient<MyApiClient>(c => c.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com"));
```

**2. Project structure**

```
src/
  MyMcpServer/
    Tools/MyTool.cs          # MCP tool, depends on MyApiClient
    Clients/MyApiClient.cs   # Wraps HttpClient calls
tests/
  MyMcpServer.Tests/
    MyToolTests.cs
```

**3. In tests, use `MockHttpMessageHandler`**

```csharp
// MyToolTests.cs
using System.Net;
using System.Net.Http;
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;

[Fact]
public async Task Tool_ReturnsExpectedResult()
{
    // Arrange — fake HTTP response
    var handler = new MockHandler(new HttpResponseMessage
    {
        StatusCode = HttpStatusCode.OK,
        Content = new StringContent("""{"id":1,"name":"Test"}""")
    });

    var httpClient = new HttpClient(handler)
    {
        BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com")
    };

    var apiClient = new MyApiClient(httpClient);
    var tool = new MyTool(apiClient);

    // Act
    var result = await tool.ExecuteAsync(/* args */);

    // Assert
    Assert.Equal("Test", result.Name);
}

// Reusable fake handler (or use NuGet: RichardSzalay.MockHttp)
class MockHandler(HttpResponseMessage response) : HttpMessageHandler
{
    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken ct)
        => Task.FromResult(response);
}
```

**Key principles:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| Isolate HTTP | Inject `HttpClient` via constructor / `IHttpClientFactory` |
| Fake responses | Swap `HttpMessageHandler` (or use **RichardSzalay.MockHttp**) |
| Test the tool | Instantiate with the faked client — no real network calls |
| Integration tests | Optionally use `WebApplicationFactory` + `ConfigureTestServices` to override the handler app-wide |

This keeps your tools testable without touching the real API, and the `MockHttp` NuGet package adds fluent request-matching if you need to verify URLs, headers, or bodies.
